<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-617-837  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 617 837.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>EDGE: Work-Group Computing Report  Nov 5 1990 v1 n24 p11(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EDGE Publishing 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Software rental: SPA-sponsored effort pays off with Congressionalprohibition. (Software Publishers Association, Software RentalAmendments Act of 1989, Copyright Clarification Act of 1990)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Topic:     LegislationIntellectual PropertyCopyrightLeasingRentingSoftware PackagesLegal IssuesUnited States. Congress.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Just hours before the 101st Congress adjourned, its members approved TheSoftware Rental Amendments Act of 1989, legislation prohibiting &quot;the rental,leasing, or lending of commercial software without the express permission ofthe copywriter holder.&quot;andM;The bill is intended to protect the intellectual property of softwarepublishers.andP;  The legislation was passed by the House of Representatives andthe U.S.andP;  Senate after a five-year lobbying effort by the software industry.andM;The recently passed bill was introduced by Congressman Mike Synar (D-OK) andby Sen.andP;  Orrin Hatch (R-UT).andP;  This legislation has been a top lobbyingpriority for the SPA and a number of its member companies.andP;  Because softwarerentals often result in pirated software, rental operations have long been ofconcern to the industry.andP;  Under the new legislation, software companies arenow permitted to restrict the commercial rental of their products.andP;  Thisprotects copyright holders against the unauthorized use and duplication oftheir copyrighted materials.andM;In related action, the Congress also passed the Copyright Clarification Actof 1990, a bill that will close a loophole that protected states from damagesuits under the U.S.andP;  Copyright Act.andP;  The correction was necessary as aresult of the Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals decision in the case of B.V.andO;Engineering vs.andP;  UCLA.andP;  In that case, brought by a software developer, thecourt ruled that states and their instrumentalities are immune from suitunder Federal copyright laws by virtue of the sovereign immunity provisionsof the 11th Amendment to the U.S.andP;  Constitution.andM;The Copyright Clarification Act of 1990 makes it clear that state governmentand state government entities can now be sued for copyright infringement, andan aggrieved copyright holder can now recover money damages, attorneys feesand receive injunctive relief.andM;The Software Publishers Association is the principal trade group of the PCsoftware industry.andP;  Its 700 members represent the leading publishers in thebusiness, consumer, and education software markets.andM;Key Executives: SPA Executive Director Ken Wasch.andP;  Tom Lemberg, chairman ofthe SPA Government Affairs Committee and Vice President and General Counselof Lotus Development Corp.andO;</TEXT></DOC>